          "body": "The Sadducees — priestly aristocrats who accepted only the Pentateuch and denied resurrection, angels, and spirits (Acts 23:8) — bring a contrived levirate scenario from Deuteronomy 25:5-10 designed to make resurrection look absurd. Jesus's reply has two layers. First (v. 30): they have misconstrued resurrection by projecting present-age categories onto the age to come — in resurrection life there is no marriage because the institution serves needs (companionship, procreation, covenantal sign) that the consummated kingdom fulfills directly. *Like the angels* does not mean bodiless; Jesus's own resurrection body (Luke 24:39) refutes that. Second, and devastating to the Sadducees on their own ground (v. 31-32): the resurrection is taught in *the Torah itself* — Exodus 3:6, where God says *I AM* (present tense) the God of patriarchs centuries dead. If God's covenant bond is to *living* persons, then Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob must yet live, which entails their resurrection. Jesus does not appeal to Daniel 12:2 or Isaiah 26:19 (which they would have rejected); He meets them on the Pentateuch alone and wins. The crowds are *astonished* (v. 33)."
